reviews.review_text: The Recording to Get The best show from 95 East Coast Summer Tour and the last time the band really delivered the goods. This is the best audience recording of the show - really clean and loud. A definite upgrade from previously available sources on this site. Nice!

last show!!!!!!!!! was my last show! but what a show it was! the rain the lightin and the band! was with a good friend thats no longer with us.. what a day thanks for the great recording and memories!!

Last Time This was not only my last show as well though a magical one to enjoy. I was there and the Rain was... unexplainable, I mean what timing. First set was a nice sunny day for a show for dancing to the likes of a rare favorite "Candy Man". Then the second came along. The sun was mellowing nicely and just at the perfect moment of when the first Rain was delivered it started to come down with heavy drops just listen for it. When they started Terrapin the stars were starting to faintly shine. If not one of then the best of the tour.It was a magical show for my Last Time.

what a show! Like many of the others, I was there for this magical night as well. What an unbelievable moment when the lightning flashed and the skies opened up at the beginning of set two! People don't believe me when I tell them that Jerry made it rain, but for those of us that were there, well...I had floor seats and because it was the middle of baseball season, they had a huge tarp covering the field(and drains). Needless to say, we were knee deep in beautiful "Rain" and groovin HARD by the middle of "Samba"! Wish I could go back there...this helps;) Peace in Your Valley

My final show It's a pretty solid performance by 1995 standards.  They sound at least competent for most of it, the only really weak point being Samba in the Rain, when Jerry basically forgot to play a solo.  There are some strong moments, like Hell in a Bucket, which wouldn't have been out of place in 1987 or 88, Bird Song, which got out there as usual, Terrapin, and Standing on the Moon.
